<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1894,2028]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,151,1257]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1894,1920]" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Description</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[353,457,1894,1920]" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Holotype</typeStatus>
Male. 
<emphasis box="[538,755,1894,1920]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">General coloration</emphasis>
. Entirely black to very dark brown, legs dark brown. 
<emphasis box="[1369,1430,1894,1920]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Head</emphasis>
. Three ocelli. Antenna missing. Compound eye holoptic with minute sparse ommatrichia, divided into upper and lower section of larger and smaller facets by slight depression. Face produced anteriorly, duck-bill-like. Clypeus + proboscis long, longer than the length of the head (can be seen folded under the head in 
<figureCitation box="[1139,1221,2002,2028]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="10.[151,250,2003,2027]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,1245,1977]" captionTargetId="figure-446@10.[159,1427,1245,1980]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 18. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, habitus. Scale bar = ca. 1.0 mm. Abbreviations: cl, clypeus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141091" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141091/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[1242,1323,2002,2028]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Thorax</emphasis>
. Mesonotum polished, shining, with a subtle median and a pair of more distinctive dorsocentral grooves. Anterior portion of grooves with thin dark brownish pruinosity forming longitudinal stripes, mesonotum more thickly pruinose laterally and anteriorly. Mesonotum largely bare with short dark sparse setae in median and dorsocentral grooves as well as laterally. Thoracic pleurae matte, very dark brown, katepisternum with patch of dorsal setae. 
<emphasis box="[1178,1238,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Legs.</emphasis>
Missing fore legs and left hind leg. Remaining legs with dense short dark setae. Hind tibia slender, spindle-shaped. Hind basitarsus slender, sausage-shaped, approximately 4.5 times as long as wide. 
<emphasis box="[921,989,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Wings</emphasis>
. 
<quantity box="[1006,1097,330,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 mm</quantity>
, slightly light brown fumose, darker anteriorly. All veins brown, anterior veins bolder, pterostigma concolorous with wing membrane. R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1341,1366,385,399]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">2+3</subScript>
short, curved, strongly divergent from R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[537,563,421,435]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">4+5</subScript>
, ending in C. Venation typical for the genus. 
<emphasis box="[1082,1195,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Abdomen.</emphasis>
With short dark hair. Terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[288,427,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,276,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[162,1425,273,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, terminalia. 19. Dorsal. 20. Ventral. 21. Posterior. 22. Lateral. 23. The classic 1934 “Surgeon’s photograph” of the Lochness Monster (photograph public domain); see etymology. Scale bar = ca. 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; p, dorsal sclerite of paramere; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141095/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Figs. 19–22</figureCitation>
). Epandrium (tergite nine) short, almost twice as broad as long with narrow, slit-like posteromedial cleft extending about 1/3 length of sclerite though sclerite creased along entire length. Epandrial lobes apically rather truncate, but with four broad, dark, triangular, posteroventrally-directed, shark-tooth-like lobes on the inner posterior edge. Gonocoxites distinctly convex, bulbous, ventrally broader than long, lacking posteromedian cleft, median projection, and lateral lobes. Gonostylus with two main lobes; a broad, flat dorsal lobe and a more ventral, slender posteriorly-projecting lobe. In posterior view (
<figureCitation box="[849,931,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,276,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[162,1425,273,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, terminalia. 19. Dorsal. 20. Ventral. 21. Posterior. 22. Lateral. 23. The classic 1934 “Surgeon’s photograph” of the Lochness Monster (photograph public domain); see etymology. Scale bar = ca. 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; p, dorsal sclerite of paramere; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141095/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), gonostylus broad, roughly diamond-shaped with broad truncate dorsal edge and dorsomedial edge black and covered in minute rasp-like teeth and ventral lobe foreshortened and difficult to see. In ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[698,778,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,276,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[162,1425,273,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, terminalia. 19. Dorsal. 20. Ventral. 21. Posterior. 22. Lateral. 23. The classic 1934 “Surgeon’s photograph” of the Lochness Monster (photograph public domain); see etymology. Scale bar = ca. 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; p, dorsal sclerite of paramere; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141095/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), ventral lobe of gonostylus slender, apically hooked, resembling neck and head of the Lochness Monster (as in the famous, albeit hoaxed, “surgeon’s photograph” of 1934).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,1257]" box="[199,415,763,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis box="[199,291,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,1257]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,460,798,825]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis &amp; Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Fitzgerald" authorityName="Fitzgerald" box="[815,1022,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xyele">
<emphasis box="[815,900,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. xyele</emphasis>
Fitzgerald
</taxonomicName>
, which previously had no clear affinity to other species (
<bibRefCitation author="Fitzgerald, S. J." box="[378,561,835,861]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" pagination="133 - 164" refId="ref9690" refString="Fitzgerald, S. J. (1998) Eighteen new species of Neotropical Plecia (Diptera: Bibionidae) and taxonomic notes on the genus. Transactions of the Entomological Society of America, 124 (2), 133 - 164." type="journal article" year="1998">Fitzgerald 1998</bibRefCitation>
); both species share the dark shining scutum, elongated mouthparts, and bilobate gonostylus with rasp-like dorsal lobe. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[747,856,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessiae">
<emphasis box="[747,856,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. nessiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the shape of the epandrium (with four triangular teeth in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[479,589,907,932]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessiae">
<emphasis box="[479,589,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. nessiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
verses two strong apically rounded lobes in 
<taxonomicName box="[1092,1177,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xyele">
<emphasis box="[1092,1177,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. xyele</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the very different shape of the gonostylus; in ventral view, the ventral lobe of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[829,939,943,968]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessiae">
<emphasis box="[829,939,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. nessiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slender with the apex hooked resembling the neck and head of the Lochness Monster (
<figureCitation box="[646,800,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,276,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[162,1425,273,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, terminalia. 19. Dorsal. 20. Ventral. 21. Posterior. 22. Lateral. 23. The classic 1934 “Surgeon’s photograph” of the Lochness Monster (photograph public domain); see etymology. Scale bar = ca. 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; p, dorsal sclerite of paramere; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141095/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Figs. 19 &amp; 23</figureCitation>
) whereas that of 
<taxonomicName box="[991,1075,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xyele">
<emphasis box="[991,1075,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. xyele</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rectangular, apically truncate, but with corners produced into acute points (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Fitzgerald, S. J." box="[692,871,1015,1041]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" pagination="133 - 164" refId="ref9690" refString="Fitzgerald, S. J. (1998) Eighteen new species of Neotropical Plecia (Diptera: Bibionidae) and taxonomic notes on the genus. Transactions of the Entomological Society of America, 124 (2), 133 - 164." type="journal article" year="1998">Fitzgerald 1998</bibRefCitation>
, Figs. 89–91). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[1036,1145,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nessiae">
<emphasis box="[1036,1145,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">P. nessiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<emphasis box="[1315,1380,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">xylele</emphasis>
-species-group (see Discussion) and will key to couplet 
<quantity box="[731,774,1050,1077]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
