<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="33" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,1257]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1087,1113]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet is derived from the name Nessie (a nickname for Scotland’s Lochness Monster) as the gonostylus in ventral view bears a striking resemblance to the neck and head of the Lochness Monster (as e.g., seen in the “Surgeon’s photograph” of 1934 (see 
<figureCitation box="[797,877,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–23" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1751,1775]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,276,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[162,1425,273,1728]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–23. P. nessiae sp. n., holotype male, terminalia. 19. Dorsal. 20. Ventral. 21. Posterior. 22. Lateral. 23. The classic 1934 “Surgeon’s photograph” of the Lochness Monster (photograph public domain); see etymology. Scale bar = ca. 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; p, dorsal sclerite of paramere; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141095/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="33">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tikkanen, A." box="[931,1104,1159,1185]" pageId="12" pageNumber="33" refId="ref11172" refString="Tikkanen, A. (2020) Loch Ness monster. Encyclopedia Britannica. Available from: https: // www. britannica. com / topic / Loch- Ness-monster-legendary-creature (accessed 17 July 2021)" type="url" year="2020">Tikkanen 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, the epandrium has a row of monstrous teeth along the posterior edge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
